**The Battle of Fractures**
*Preface*

* **Jochi = Kingmaker of Kings**
* **Genghis Khan = King of Kings**
* 1227 = Dual collapse of the empire‚Äôs core
* B√∂rte and Tolui face a power vacuum
* Jochi‚Äôs three sons are not yet chosen ‚Üí the Kurultai cannot convene
* The empire enters a ‚Äúsystemic vacuum‚Äù

In 1227, the Mongol Empire plunged abruptly into an abyss. The burden on Tem√ºjin‚Äôs heart was already heavy, but fate proved even harsher: his eldest son, Jochi, the first Kingmaker of Kings, suddenly died in the Golden Horde. When the news reached all corners of Mongolia, Tem√ºjin himself had already passed away at Xingqing Prefecture in the Daxia‚Äîwithin the same year, the King of Kings and the Kingmaker of Kings fell in succession. For the empire, this was an unprecedented political earthquake.

As Khatun, B√∂rte was filled with fear and uncertainty. Losing the support of her eldest son meant that her youngest son, Tolui, became the sole hope. Yet under the laws of the steppe, she had no authority to interfere in the succession of the Golden Horde‚Äôs khanship. She was left with a difficult choice: appoint her young son Tolui as regent, while waiting for Jochi‚Äôs sons‚ÄîOrda, Berke, and Batu‚Äîto decide who would become the new Kingmaker of Kings of the Golden Horde.

From 1227 to 1229, the Mongol Empire resembled a colossal beast without a heart: without the support of the Kingmaker of Kings, the throne of the King of Kings remained unoccupied, and the Kurultai could not convene. The empire entered a period of blankness; the inertia of power was completely broken. Anxiety spread among the people, and the loyalty and order of the Mongol pastoralists wavered. B√∂rte and Tolui could only carefully maintain a fragile surface stability amid the crisis.

Ultimately, the succession dispute in the Golden Horde dragged on until 1235, when Batu, through perseverance and strategy, prevailed‚Äîfinally securing the position of Kingmaker of Kings and restoring a measure of order to the Mongol Empire. But the lesson was profound: the life or death of an empire often hinges on the gaps in institutional design and the transfer of power.

For this reason, the United States goes to great lengths in institutional design to avoid overlapping congressional and presidential elections. Even if a president dies or resigns, the remaining term must be completed according to the line of succession, to prevent a power vacuum from leading to national ‚Äúcollapse.‚Äù The history of the Mongol Empire reminds the world: even the smallest fissures in institutions and succession can determine the survival or demise of a civilization.



Europe has long attempted to portray the Mongol Empire as a highly centralized state, as if only a supreme central authority could explain its immense power. In reality, the opposite is true: the terrifying military capability of the Mongols stemmed from a highly evolved military-political complex. By contrast, although the Song dynasty enjoyed commercial prosperity, its military-political complex had long been filtered down to just craftsmen and merchants; the military system had been eliminated. This did not make the Song indifferent to the Mongols‚Äîit made them unable to fully comprehend the efficiency and evolutionary logic of the Mongol military-political complex.

At its core, the Mongol Empire was an experiment in pushing the limits of abandoning bloodline-based rule. Its territory at one point surpassed that of the Tang dynasty, and the military-political complex experiment was a success: cultural sovereignty and military power were separated for the first time, yet remained highly coordinated. Even when most of Eurasia fell under Mongol control, Tem√ºjin did not invade the Song border, demonstrating the strategic discipline and institutionalization of the Mongol Empire.

However, in 1227, the deaths of both the Kingmaker of Kings and the King of Kings in the same year dealt a severe blow to this political experiment. By 1229, √ñgedei, in alliance with Chagatai, forced B√∂rte‚Äôs son Tolui to relinquish his regency and claimed the title of King of Kings for himself. The following year, B√∂rte passed away, and internal disorder in the Mongol Empire was left unchecked. Although Tolui‚Äôs military achievements far surpassed √ñgedei‚Äôs and he inherited most of Tem√ºjin‚Äôs forces, he could not directly prevent the restructuring of power.

In 1232, √ñgedei orchestrated a campaign in which Tolui and he jointly attacked the remnants of the Jin dynasty, defeating 150,000 Jin cavalry with 40,000 Mongol horsemen, thus cementing √ñgedei‚Äôs military reputation. On the return journey, Tolui was poisoned, and his forces and authority were transferred to √ñgedei‚Äôs son, Kurey. This blatantly violated the laws of the steppe, yet it also revealed that the symbiotic relationship between the Golden Horde and the King of Kings had broken down: the party controlling the strongest military force no longer cared about proxies or the distribution of imperial interests.

Between 1235 and 1242, the Golden Horde invaded Europe, and military merit became the practical criterion for succession to the Kingmaker of Kings, rather than formal institutional rules. After √ñgedei‚Äôs death in 1241, his wife T√∂regene took charge of governance until 1246, ensuring that their son G√ºy√ºk ascended as King of Kings. From beginning to end, these events violated the steppe laws: the elevation of the King of Kings occurred without the consent of the Kingmaker of Kings, but the Golden Horde realized the transfer of power through military accomplishments, control of armed forces, and political reality.




### **The Black Wind of 1248: Q√ºy√º‚Äôs Decision and the Echoes of the Mongol Empire**

In the early spring of 1248, the sky over Khara-Khorin was gray like a sheet of pressed iron.
Q√ºy√º sat inside the Great Khan‚Äôs tent, fingertips tapping lightly on the edge of the map. He knew the throne of the King of Kings he occupied was bright‚Äîbut as thin as ice. True power did not reside here; it lay further west, at the edge of the steppe, in the colossal force controlled by the descendants of Jochi.

**The Golden Horde‚Äîthe nest of the Shatuo military-industrial complex.**
This was neither a ‚Äúvassal state‚Äù nor a ‚Äúborder power.‚Äù It was the heart of the other half of the empire, the position Tem√ºjin had deliberately created for his eldest son: the Kingmaker of Kings. Q√ºy√º knew clearly that as long as that half existed, he would forever be a proxy‚Äîallowed to sit in the seat, but never truly owning it.

So he made a decision that could almost be called ‚Äúsuicidal.‚Äù

**Westward‚Äîeradicate the Golden Horde, uproot the Shatuo system.**
Q√ºy√º understood that once he destroyed them, he would no longer have to abide by the laws of the steppe, no longer watch Batu‚Äôs face, no longer serve as King of Kings under the shadow of the Shatuo military-industrial complex. He needed a reckoning, a complete rupture.

One hundred thousand troops were assembled‚Äîsilent, dry, like blood hardened by the wind.
This was the first truly ruthless declaration he made to the entire Mongol Empire.

---

### **Whispers of Sor√ºteni**

Tolui had long been dead, yet his shadow still roamed the night of the Mongol Empire.
Tolui‚Äôs widow, Sor√ºteni, understood that Q√ºy√º‚Äôs expedition was no ordinary campaign‚Äîit was a declaration of war against the entire Shatuo system, against the entire law of the steppe.

She swallowed her hesitation and sent the wind westward‚Äîto Batu.

No drums, no horns‚Äîonly a secret messenger cutting across the steppe.

When Batu received the news, he was leaning in a pine chair by the Volga River. In that instant, there was no surprise in his eyes, only a cold certainty:
**‚ÄúIt has come. It has finally come.‚Äù**

For Q√ºy√º‚Äôs blade was bound to fall sooner or later.

---

### **The Iron Flow in the West and Hesitation in the East**

Batu did not wait for the winter snows to melt. He mobilized one hundred thousand troops, augmented by the knights of the Moscow principality.
He understood‚Äîif Q√ºy√º reached the outskirts of the Golden Horde, the Jochi line would be wiped out in an instant; the Shatuo military-political system would be dismantled to its very bones.

Yet on the other side of the steppe, Q√ºy√º‚Äôs hundred-thousand-strong army, though imposing, carried a strange anxiety.

They had no certainty of victory.
No confidence to face the Shatuo system head-on.
All they could rely on was ‚Äúsurprise‚Äù and Q√ºy√º‚Äôs determination.

Thus, the army advanced westward with the mentality of gamblers.

---

### **The Arrival of Death**

But Q√ºy√º never reached the battlefield.

Halfway, he died.
Cause unknown.
The most common explanation on the steppe was:

**‚ÄúThe moment he decided, he was already dead.‚Äù**

As if some immense structure would not allow him to cross its boundary.

At the instant the army heard the news, it was as if its backbone had been pulled out‚Äîthey quickly disintegrated.
No one was willing to continue westward to die for Q√ºy√º.
They had always been mere pieces in a hastily arranged, hysterical war.

Batu‚Äôs forces reached the border steadily, only to find the battle unnecessary.
The enemy had already scattered on its own.

---

### **The Echoes of the Empire**

The news of Q√ºy√º‚Äôs death reached Khara-Khorin, and the Mongol tribes withdrew like tides‚Äî
No one wanted to bear the consequences for a Great Khan who was already dead, and no one dared provoke the Shatuo system.

At that moment, the Mongol Empire revealed a truth it had never fully acknowledged:

**Whoever controls the military-political complex is the true master of the empire.**

Q√ºy√º‚Äôs death was sudden, yet inevitable.
He had challenged the other half of the empire, and that half was not a collection of tribes‚Äîit was a structure, an older, colder, more resolute power than he could confront.




## **The Takeover of the Golden Horde (1250‚Äì1260)**

Q√ºy√º‚Äôs death made the steppe winds suddenly lighter, yet also suddenly colder.
The war that had not truly begun was over‚Äîbut it revealed a deeper and more dangerous fact:

**The Golden Horde was ready to no longer tolerate a disobedient proxy.**

---

### **1250: M√∂ngke‚Äôs Westward Journey**

In the winter of 1250, Tolui‚Äôs son‚ÄîM√∂ngke‚Äîleft Khara-Khorin on a snowy night.
This was no ceremonial visit; it was a knock on the door carried with fear and a gamble.

He went to see Batu‚Äîto see the ‚ÄúKingmaker of Kings.‚Äù
More precisely, he was going to meet the true stakeholder behind the Shatuo military-political complex.

M√∂ngke‚Äôs core request was simple:

**‚ÄúPermit us to attack the Song Empire.‚Äù**

To outsiders, this seemed like a mere military plan.
But within the Mongol Empire, it was a highly dangerous template integration:

* The Shatuo military-political complex had a template in the west (steppe warfare ‚Üí logistics ‚Üí deep penetration ‚Üí colonization).
* Behind the Song imperial house lay another ultimate template (advanced logistics ‚Üí technical craftsmen ‚Üí urban warfare structures).

**What would happen if the two templates merged?**
M√∂ngke did not know.
But the Golden Horde did.
And that was precisely what made them hesitate, scrutinize, and even fear.

---

### **1251: The Golden Horde Cavalry Enters Khara-Khorin**

In the spring of 1251, Berke, dispatched by Batu, led 100,000 cavalry into Khara-Khorin.

That day, dust swirled beneath the city walls like a warning forged from steel and storm.

**The Golden Horde officially began intervening in the succession of Mongol Empire proxies.**

M√∂ngke was enthroned as the new ‚ÄúKing of Kings.‚Äù
But everyone understood:

* He was not a sovereign, but the **first CEO**;
* The Golden Horde was the **chairman + majority shareholder (70%)**;
* The Mongol Empire had been re-integrated as the ‚Äúfront-end execution layer‚Äù of the Shatuo system.

Then came the purge.

A midnight storm uprooting the old order:

* Q√ºy√º‚Äôs wife, Haymis, executed.
* Hucha and Naohu exiled to Central Asia and the Iranian plateau.
* √ñgedei‚Äôs grandson, Shirimen, killed.
* Chagatai‚Äôs direct line‚ÄîSut M√∂ngke and Buri‚Äîalso executed.

**The laws of the steppe were replaced by the Golden Horde.**
The old order of the Golden family was completely deleted by the Shatuo military-industrial complex.

At that moment, the Mongol Empire became, for the first time, a **truly joint-stock empire**.

---

### **But one question went unasked:**

**‚ÄúAfter conquering the Song Empire, what will the two templates merge into?‚Äù**

The Golden Horde had not thought this through‚Äî
Or perhaps they had, but refused to admit it:

> This would be a technical explosion capable of overturning the entire Golden family.

---

### **1259: Death Before Diaoyu Fortress**

M√∂ngke died in the mist and rain of the Sichuan basin, at the edge of the Song Empire‚Äôs military template, at the moment when the two templates were about to merge.

His death was like an axe, cleaving the entire strategic situation into fragments.

For the Jochi family, it was the first realization:

**The Shatuo military-political complex was devouring the Golden family.**

Not a conspiracy, but evolution.
Not murder, but elimination.

---

### **Berke‚Äôs Roar: The Awakening of the Golden Family**

When the news reached the Golden Horde, Berke remained silent for a long time.
That silence was like the spine of a knife in the night.

Finally, he roared:

**‚ÄúYou deceived us?‚Äù**

The answer came from the master of the Mo school, the silent observer who had always stood behind cultural sovereignty.

He replied calmly:

**‚ÄúNo, we have spoken only the truth.
But we answer only the questions you ask.
You never asked:
‚ÄòUnder cultural sovereignty, do we still need bloodlines?‚Äô‚Äù**

Berke was stunned.

The voice of the Mo master seemed to come from the depths of a millennia-old system:

**‚ÄúUnder cultural sovereignty, there is no bloodline.
And there is no concept of Genghis Khan‚Äôs descendants.
You are only the initial carrier, not the final form.‚Äù**

In that moment, the Golden Horde realized for the first time:

**They were cooperating with a structure that existed purely for evolution‚Äîbeyond blood, beyond loyalty.
And this structure had already begun to consider eliminating them.**




## üî• **1260‚Äì1269: The Collapse of Steppe Order and the Shatuo‚ÄìGolden Horde System Enters the ‚ÄúAnti-Kublai Alliance Era‚Äù**

**The Mongol Empire did not collapse because of external enemies, but because the Great Khan sought to destroy the military-industrial complex (the Shatuo‚ÄìGolden Horde system) and discovered he had no authority to do so.**

---

### **‚ë† 1260: Ariq Boke Ascends, the Great Khan‚Äôs Power Becomes a Hollow Shell**

Ariq Boke represented:

* Steppe traditional succession law (Khuriltai)
* The steppe tribal cavalry system (already in decline)
* The old political center of Khara-Khorin (lacking an economic base)

Kublai represented:

* Agrarian finance (Central Plains)
* Han military-industrial and supply chains (Northern Han forces becoming primary)
* Coalition diplomacy with the other khanates (supported by Hulegu)

**Ariq Boke represented the old steppe era; from day one, Kublai was no longer a product of the Mongol system.**

---

### **‚ë° Kublai‚Äôs Greatest Crisis: His Rebellion ‚ÄúScared the Mongols Away‚Äù**

**Once Kublai rebelled, the Mongol herders fled immediately because they knew he was establishing a ‚Äúnon-steppe order.‚Äù**

More fatally:
**Mongol forces on the Southern Song front (already heavily Han and Khitan) defected to the Song army.**

This is a historical fact seldom told: what Kublai was really doing was the largest-scale **military-political system transition in Mongol war history.**

He had no choice but to replace 60% of his army with Northern Han troops. This was not ‚Äúpreference‚Äù‚Äîit was **necessity.**

From that moment on:

**Mongol Empire = dead
Yuan Dynasty = a state ruled by Mongol blood but essentially a Han military-industrial system.**

---

### **‚ë¢ 1262‚Äì1264: Golden Horde vs Ilkhanate (essentially a struggle over who controlled the Shatuo military-industrial system)**

* Golden Horde (closest to the Shatuo military system)
* Ilkhanate (Hulegu relied entirely on Persian finance and Near Eastern military industry)

Victories south of the Caucasus proved one thing: **the Golden Horde‚Äôs production system was more hardcore than the Iranian military-industrial system.**

Meanwhile, Kublai struggled in the east because:

* His army was a multi-ethnic mixed force
* Supply chains were overextended
* The Central Plains‚Äô finances were not fully under his control

Yet in 1264 he captured Khara-Khorin and eliminated Ariq Boke: **this was not a Mongol Empire victory‚Äîit was the empire‚Äôs funeral.**

Kublai declared independence, abolished the steppe law, and renamed the state **‚ÄúGreat Yuan, Great Mongol State.‚Äù**

This also directly marked: **Genghis Khan‚Äôs grandchildren had ended the Mongol Empire.**

---

### **‚ë£ 1266‚Äì1269: The Golden Horde Becomes Leader of the ‚ÄúAnti-Yuan Alliance‚Äù**

Here is a crucial point:

**In 1266, after Berke died, Mengu-Timur succeeded him.
He was not a successor to the Mongol Empire, but a successor to the ‚ÄúShatuo‚ÄìGolden Horde military-industrial empire.‚Äù**

So when Kublai ordered the Golden Horde to send troops to assist in attacking Kaidu‚Ä¶
**it became, of course, a century‚Äôs joke.**

In this logic, Kublai was:

> a man who rose through the Central Plains‚Äô military-industrial system,
> yet believed he could command the steppe‚Äôs military-political complex.

It was like a CEO leaving a company to start a new business, but thinking he could still deploy the old company‚Äôs R&D department.

---

### **‚ë§ 1269: The Treaty of Talas‚ÄîThe Historical Endgame**

This treaty essentially established one fact: **the Mongol Empire was not ‚Äúsplit,‚Äù it was deconstructed by the Golden Horde.**

The Ilkhanate, Chagatai Khanate, and √ñgedei Khanate all became ‚Äúindependent states under the Golden Horde‚Äôs security umbrella.‚Äù

In other words:

> **Kublai built a state;
> the Golden Horde built a system.**

States die; systems endure.

---

### **Summary**

* Q√ºy√º tried to destroy the Shatuo military-industrial system ‚Üí he was doomed
* Ariq Boke was the last struggle of steppe institutions
* Kublai abandoned steppe law completely ‚Üí the Mongol Empire died
* The Golden Horde inherited the military-industrial system ‚Üí became the Eurasian system‚Äôs dominant power
* Ilkhanate, Chagatai, and √ñgedei Khanates redefined themselves under the Golden system
* After 1269, the Mongol Empire was no longer a state, but a network of military-industrial‚Äìfiscal complexes







### Stage Play: **‚ÄúYou Should Leave Now, and Never Come Back‚Äù**

**Time:** 1294
**Location:** In the truce-negotiation tent at the boundary between the two armies outside Karakorum, the former capital of the Mongol Empire
**Event:** Peace negotiations between the Great Yuan / Great Mongol State and the ‚ÄúAnti‚ÄìGreat Yuan Great Mongol State Alliance‚Äù

**Delegates of the Great Yuan / Great Mongol State:**

* Kublai Khan (78 years old)
* Prince of Beiping, Namqan, Kublai‚Äôs fourth son (held as a hostage by the Golden Horde from 1277 to 1285)

**Delegates of the Anti‚ÄìGreat Yuan Great Mongol State Alliance:**

* Tsar Toqta of the Golden Horde
* Representative of the Military-Industrial Complex: the Grand Master of the Mohist School
* Kaidu, Khan of the √ñgedeid Khanate
* Duwa, Khan of the Chagatai Khanate




## **Act I**

**[Stage]**
Outside Karakorum, a frozen steppe.
The boundary between the two opposing armies is marked by a silent white line.
Cold wind lashes the great tent, making the felt walls snap and ripple.

Inside, a dim butter lamp flickers.
Kublai Khan sits on a cushion, leaning on his cane‚Äîlike an ancient stone stele about to collapse.

---

### **Kublai (hoarse, but still burning with anger)**

For the sake of evolution‚Ä¶
Are you not afraid
that even the Golden Family could be eliminated?

(He lifts his head; his eyes are clouded, but a stubborn spark still fights to survive.)

---

### **Toqta (a cold, contemptuous laugh)**

You‚Äôre afraid?
You only learn fear at *your age*?

(He steps toward Namqan, staring at him the way one examines a frail young horse.)

When this child of yours was a hostage in Kiev‚Ä¶
Did he ever see a single one of my men
fear being eliminated?

Your father wasn‚Äôt ‚Äúevolving.‚Äù
He was‚Äî

**securing for you descendants a cheap, safe, competition-free hereditary throne.**





Namukhan tried to speak, but Kublai raised a hand to stop him.

---

### **Kublai (hoarse, nearly gasping)**

Moists‚Ä¶
I ask you‚Äî

(He fixes his gaze on the Moist Grandmaster, as if staring at an old god without a soul.)

Did you not, long ago, promise my grandfather, Tem√ºjin,
to help him build‚Ä¶
**an empire without bloodlines, without hereditary succession, governed solely by cultural sovereignty?**

I remember you saying it.
You said it would be a new order for humankind.

---

### **Moist Grandmaster (voice calm to the point of coldness)**

Genghis Khan demanded ‚Äúorder.‚Äù
What we gave him was a ‚Äúformula.‚Äù

As for your Golden Family‚Ä¶
Whether you could keep pace with the formula
was never part of the plan.

(He pauses, as if stating a law of nature.)

You are being eliminated.
It is not betrayal.
It is‚Äî
**a natural consequence.**

---

Kublai felt as if a knife had pierced his chest; his shoulder trembled.




### **Kaidu (indifferent, like an old wolf who has seen it all)**

Kublai, you think too much.
You were not forced into rebellion by us;
you forced yourself into it.

You wanted Han bureaucracy, Song taxation, Persian astronomy, and the steppe army‚Ä¶
One man, greedy to this extent,
is bound to be rejected by all systems at once.

---

### **Duwa (wearily mocking)**

We‚Äôre only telling you in advance‚Äî
**you are no longer part of the Steppe.**

---

### **Kublai (suddenly erupting, voice trembling but forceful)**

Then what do you want me to do?
Do you want the Yuan to be like you‚Äî
endlessly fighting within, endlessly purging, endlessly pushing the Golden Family toward the cliff?

