Is that‚Ä¶ so unreasonable?!

---

### **Moist Grandmaster (emotionless)**

You‚Äôve misunderstood the question.

**We do not oppose continuity.**
What we oppose is‚Äî
you using continuity as a justification for power.

Power belongs only to the nodes that can maintain the speed of evolution,
not to a surname.

---

Kublai felt as if all his strength had been drained, collapsing back onto the cushion.

He looked at the four of them, his eyes asking silently:
*"What have I been holding on to all these years?"*

The four remained silent.
They would not answer.
Because they knew‚Äî
Kublai was no longer entitled to hear the answer.




### **Act II**

Kublai spoke in a hoarse, choking whisper:
*"If evolution can even eliminate itself, then what use is this evolution to me?"*

The Moist Grandmaster was about to respond when Toqta cut in:
*"What we want is this: even if our descendants are no longer kings or nobles, even if they are commoners, they can freely do what they wish. You know us well‚Äîyou know we cannot afford to take unnecessary risks. To be an emperor? Where does the Mongol Empire leave an emperor? When Genghis Khan was alive, he had already divided half the empire to establish the Golden Horde. Are you not afraid your descendants, if they fail in competition, will live worse than a dog? Under cultural sovereignty, taking risks is the only way to achieve greatness. And if you change the emperor, if your generals succeed in a coup, what happens to your descendants? If the slaves rebel successfully, what then?"*

Kublai froze, as if Toqta had struck a nerve he had long pretended did not exist.

**Kublai (softly):**
*"‚Ä¶But isn‚Äôt the empire itself built to prevent us from being eliminated?"*

Toqta smiled bitterly, a smile tinged with the Steppe‚Äôs unique clarity and fatalism.

**Toqta:**
*"Empire? Khans? These are all conveniences. You don‚Äôt really think Genghis Khan conquered the world so his great-grandsons could hold a fixed palace position called 'emperor,' do you?
We Mongols have no illusions of 'dynastic perpetuity.' We only believe‚Äî**opportunity is always outside, never on the throne.**"*

Only then did the Moist Grandmaster speak, his voice calm yet carrying the weight of judgment:

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"Institutions are not guarantees‚Äîthey are gambling tables.
Your choice is this:
‚ÄîDo you want a civilization that can replicate, evolve, and expand?
‚ÄîOr do you want a fixed, frozen order centered around yourself?
These two will always be in conflict."*





Kublai‚Äôs brow tightened, like a beast cornered against a wall.

**Kublai:**
*"But I‚Ä¶ I just want a place where my descendants can have shelter from the storm."*

This time Toqta almost shouted:

**Toqta:**
*"Shelter from the storm? That‚Äôs the mindset of farmers!
A child of the Steppe, give him a horse and a bow, and he will carve out his own sky!
If you build a vast empire to trap them, you are cutting off their legs!"*

He paused, staring Kublai down:

**Toqta (pressing):**
*"Do you dare guarantee that your descendants will hold the throne for generations?
Do you dare guarantee they won‚Äôt be slaughtered worse than dogs in some coup?
Do you dare guarantee that a thousand years from now, Mongols will still recognize your bloodline?"*

Kublai fell silent.

The Moist Grandmaster slowly stepped closer, his tone offering a final choice:

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"Evolution is not meant to give you comfort; it is meant so that your descendants, **even if they lose everything, will still have a future.**
The empire‚Äôs mission is not to protect your status,
but to ensure‚Äî
**your cultural modules can restart anywhere in the world.**
As long as civilization can be backed up, your descendants will never truly die."*

Kublai lifted his head, eyes pained and hesitant:

**Kublai:**
*"But‚Ä¶ if evolution can discard even me, then what‚Ä¶ what am I?"*

Toqta slowly crouched down to meet his gaze‚Äîan honesty shared only between Steppe brothers:

**Toqta:**
*"What are you?
You are‚Äî
**a node of this civilization.**
Not the main server."*

The air instantly turned as cold as a northern winter night.

**Toqta (softly):**
*"The power of the Mongols has never been a Khan alone; it is this entire way of life that can spread across the world.
If you try to sit on an eternal throne, what will ultimately be destroyed is not yourself‚Äî
but the very ‚Äòreplicability‚Äô of this civilization."*




## **Act Three**

Kublai felt as if someone had shoved him violently from behind; he stumbled forward a step, his throat trembling:

**Kublai (almost shouting):**
*"The Song Empire! The Song Empire! Their emperor isn‚Äôt eliminated‚Äîwhy can‚Äôt we be the same?!"*

For a moment, Toqta‚Äôs expression softened with a pity that said, *‚ÄúYou really still don‚Äôt understand.‚Äù*

**Toqta:**
*"The youngest son of the Torei clan‚Äîyou think we‚Äôre fools?
The Song state an empire? The Song state doesn‚Äôt even have an *emperor*."*

Kublai froze: *‚Äú‚Ä¶What?‚Äù*

Toqta stepped forward, lowering his voice, as if revealing a truth everyone knew except Kublai:

**Toqta:**
*"That so-called emperor of the Song‚Äîyou ever seen him issue an edict?
They don‚Äôt have edicts at all.
Without the signatures of the Secretariat, Chancellery, and Privy Council, he can‚Äôt even repair his own house."*

The Moist Grandmaster quietly added, his tone as calm as a weather report, yet each sentence pierced illusions like a blade:

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"The emperor of the Song isn‚Äôt ‚Äònot eliminated‚Äô‚Äî
*he has never been on the decision-making chain.*
What gets eliminated isn‚Äôt the person‚Äîit‚Äôs the position.
They eliminate power itself, not the one sitting in that chair."*

Kublai froze completely.

For the first time, he realized:

**The Song did not preserve the emperor‚Äîthe Song abolished the ‚Äòemperor‚Äô as a position.**






## **Act Four**

Kublai slammed his hand on the table, his voice hoarse:
*"And you still approved M√∂ngke‚Äôs campaign against the Song Empire?! You knew full well we would die like that!"*

The Moist Grandmaster looked at him without flinching, his face carrying a calm certainty, as if saying, *‚ÄúThis is something you must understand.‚Äù*

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"They no longer answer to us, Kublai.
The Song civilization has evolved into a *logistics-driven civilization*.
A massive machine that runs on waterways, artisan communities, and large-scale, meticulous division of labor."*

He paused, letting Kublai feel the harsh reality that *the world had changed*.

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"In this civilization, the navy is highly developed, and supply lines move ten times faster than your steppe logistics.
Don‚Äôt play dumb.
Didn‚Äôt you attack by trying to avoid their coastline?
Nibbling your way in from the Sichuan Basin?
How many of your people died? A hundred thousand? Two hundred thousand? Or a million?"*

Kublai gritted his teeth, his eyes filled with pain, shame, and a sense of utter abandonment.

**Kublai:**
*"You‚Äôre mocking us!"*





The Moist Grandmaster shook his head, showing for the first time a genuine helplessness.

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"No.
For all adventurers, our principle has always been‚Äî
**never to point out the risk.**
We don‚Äôt want to dampen the spirit of those willing to take chances."*

Kublai‚Äôs eyes widened.
*"A principle?! This is using a knife through someone else‚Äôs hand!"*

But the Moist Grandmaster completely ignored his anger, continuing in that calm explanatory tone, as if reading a verdict on behalf of history itself.

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"It‚Äôs just‚Ä¶ very clearly, you never listened carefully when the Song officials explained their system.
You twisted everything your way.
You wouldn‚Äôt listen.
You only hear what you want to hear."*

Kublai looked as if struck by a whip, his face collapsing.

The Moist Grandmaster continued, his voice now tinged with a hint of regret:

**Moist Grandmaster:**
*"Over these past years, thanks to your constant tinkering and meddling,
a large number of Song military-industrial complex members
migrated alongside the Mongol herders who left you,
moving through Central and Northern Asia,
and eventually ended up in the Golden Horde."*

Kublai froze, as if stabbed through the heart.

He panted, chest heaving, and finally hoarsely shouted:

**Kublai:**
*"Go! Everyone go!
Tell me‚Äî
who do you still value now?!
Make me a list, one by one!"*

He pointed outside the tent, like an old beast-king roaring in his dying moments:

**Kublai:**
*"Since you‚Äôre leaving‚Äî
**don‚Äôt ever come back!**"*

The tent instantly fell into a deathly silence.

Toqta, Kaidu, and Duwa didn‚Äôt utter a word‚Äî
but each of them wore the expression: *‚ÄúYou said this far too late.‚Äù*




## **Act Five**

**Toqta stood up coldly, as if delivering a verdict:**
*"I know when you return, you will tell everyone‚Äî
that you have won."*

He turned to Kublai, his tone devoid of hatred, yet carrying a sorrow from the depths of the steppe, almost like a clan elder addressing a child who has lost their way:

**Toqta:**
*"The youngest son of the Torei family, go.
Go back and be your emperor.
If you want to be emperor, then be emperor.
But remember‚Äî
**the Mongolian Plateau‚Äîyou and your descendants will never return.**"*

Kublai froze as if struck; his breath caught.

**Toqta continued, merciless:**
*"You can deceive the Chinese, claim yourself the victor.
You can build palaces, run the imperial exams, paint dragons on thrones, dress in Han court robes.
They will believe you; whatever you say, they will comply."*

Toqta lowered his voice:

*"But what happens when your descendants lose?
When they lose officials, lose cities, lose granaries?"*

He pointed north, toward the vast steppe.

**Toqta:**
*"Mongolia will not support them.
We never will.
They cannot return, and they cannot endure.
They will be crushed between slave uprisings and Mongol battle lines‚Äî
**squeezed to death like dogs.**"*

Even the wind in the tent seemed to pause.

Kublai tried to protest, opened his mouth, but no words came out.

**Kaidu sneered:**
*"The emperor is a good thing; once you get used to it, you can‚Äôt go back.
We have no emperors; we only have win or lose, life or death.
You want both‚Äîyour descendants‚Ä¶ naturally, they lose both."*

Duwa of the Chagatai Khanate added:

**Duwa:**
*"You Torei family‚Ä¶ never considered that you yourselves could be eliminated."*

Kublai‚Äôs eyes suddenly welled with tears, but he forced himself to lift his head, letting no one see.

**Kublai (almost brokenly):**
*"‚Ä¶Go.
Go.
All of you, go.
Since you do not want me‚Äî
do not ever return."*

Toqta nodded slightly, as if completing the hardest ceremony of his life:

**Toqta:**
*"We will not return.
Rest assured."*

He turned, lifted the tent flap, and the wind and snow poured in.
The cold steppe wind cut through time itself, like a blade tearing eras apart.




**Narrator**

Shortly after returning to the capital of the Great Yuan Mongol Empire, Beijing, Kublai passed away.
The eleven emperors of the Great Yuan Mongol Empire struggled endlessly to reorganize political alliances, trying to prevent the Mongol nomads from fracturing, yet they could not repair the rift in the steppe.

When the Chinese overthrew the empire, few Mongol nomads responded to the court‚Äôs call to suppress the uprising.

The Yuan regime was forced to flee to Hohhot and establish a secondary capital, never daring to set foot on the true Mongolian Plateau again.

When the Ming cavalry advanced north, sweeping across the steppe gateways like a storm,
**the Great Yuan Mongol Empire was utterly destroyed.**

The curtain falls.
The End.






